zenwebp ARM (aarch64) hot-path profile — 2026-05-30
====================================================

Host:        Hetzner cax21, aarch64 Ampere/Neoverse-N1, 4 cores, 7.5 GB RAM
Base commit: zenwebp main@origin fe4102ab7cfb
Toolchain:   cargo 1.96.0, rustc stable, edition 2024
Build (lib/bench):   RUSTFLAGS="" cargo build --release -j2   (honest runtime dispatch, NOT target-cpu=native)
Build (profiling):   RUSTFLAGS="-C force-frame-pointers=yes" CARGO_PROFILE_RELEASE_DEBUG=1 \
                     cargo build --release --features _profiling --example arm_profile -j2
Profiler:    perf 6.8.x, `perf record -F 1999 -g` (frame pointers),
             `perf report --no-children`, `perf annotate`
Corpus:      codec-corpus crate cache v1 (real images),
             CODEC_CORPUS_DIR=$HOME/.cache/codec-corpus/v1
Image:       gb82-sc/codec_wiki.png (2560x1664 screenshot, 4.26 MP)

BENCH UNBLOCK (what was broken, what was fixed)
-----------------------------------------------
Baseline blocker: every zenwebp bench resolved the corpus through a hardcoded
default path "/home/lilith/work/codec-corpus" that exists on no CI/dev runner.
- encode_benchmark / encode_vs_libwebp / profile_encode: codec_corpus_dir()
  asserted dir.is_dir() on that path and PANICKED out-of-the-box.
- decode_benchmark / decode_zenbench / decode_compare / decode_lossless_compare
  / predictor_coalesce: use codec_corpus::Corpus directly; they silently skip
  every image when the crate cannot resolve a populated cache.

Fix shipped (this change):
- benches/encode_benchmark.rs and benches/encode_vs_libwebp.rs: codec_corpus_dir()
  now resolves the corpus root in the same order the codec-corpus crate uses, so
  it works out-of-the-box wherever the crate's cache is populated:
    1. CODEC_CORPUS_DIR  (explicit override, points directly at the root)
    2. CODEC_CORPUS_CACHE/codec-corpus/v1  (the crate's cache env var)
    3. $HOME/.cache/codec-corpus/v1        (the crate's default cache location)
  (No private codec-corpus internals are touched: Corpus.root is a private field
   with no public accessor, so the path is reconstructed via the documented
   {cache}/codec-corpus/v{MAJOR} layout — confirmed in codec-corpus 1.1.0 source,
   Corpus::init at src/lib.rs.)
- The decode benches are unblocked by pointing CODEC_CORPUS_DIR (or
  CODEC_CORPUS_CACHE) at the populated cache — the crate's standard mechanism;
  no code change is needed there.

Verification on the ARM box (base fe4102ab, RUSTFLAGS=""):
- `cargo build --release` (lib): OK
- `cargo build --release --benches`: all benches compile.
- decode_benchmark runs against real images (no "skipping ... not found in
  corpus") with CODEC_CORPUS_DIR set. The criterion encode bench is functional
  but slow on the 4 MP screenshot; the arm_profile driver below is the fast,
  perf-friendly alternative used for the numbers in this report.

WALL-CLOCK (arm_profile driver, /usr/bin/time -v, codec_wiki 2560x1664)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
- decode RGBA:    20.92 s / 600 iters = 34.9 ms/decode  (~122 Mpix/s)
- encode m4 q75:  ~30 s   /  80 iters = ~380 ms/encode  (4.26 MP screenshot)
- max RSS:        47 MB

PROFILE (self %, perf report --no-children; see .tsv for the table)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
decode top-3: upsample 23.84% | loop_filter(V+H) 12.78% | idct 8.43%
              (bit_reader 7.62% + tree 6.91% + residual 5.21% = serial bool coder/coeff parse)
encode top-3: cost::get_residual_cost 19.43% | simd::evaluate_i4 14.21% | encode_image 11.08%
              (record_coeff 9.34% = serial token recording)

OPTIMIZATION OUTCOME: HONEST-STOP — no measured ARM win available
----------------------------------------------------------------
Every vectorizable hot kernel on BOTH paths is already SIMD via archmage
#[arcane]/#[rite] + magetypes, with the `neon` tier present in each kernel's tier
list. `perf annotate` on the #1 decode hotspot (upsample, 23.84%) confirms NEON
is actually executing on aarch64 (exclusive-sample instruction histogram):
  ld1{v.16b}, add v, umull, ushll, st1, uzp1, mul v, urhadd, uqxtn, zip1, tbl,
  umlal, sqrshrun, zip2, uzp2 ...
i.e. widening multiply-accumulate (YUV->RGB fixed point), de/interleave
(planar<->packed), rounding halving add (bilinear), saturating narrow (output),
and table lookup — a fully-vectorized kernel.

The hotspots that are NOT vectorized are inherently serial and already
micro-optimized per the codebase's documented history (zenwebp/CLAUDE.md):
  - decode bit_reader / tree / residual: VP8 boolean arithmetic decoder + coeff
    parse. Documented branchless / flat-table / deferred-refill attempts are all
    net-negative; the branches are highly biased and predict well.
  - encode cost::get_residual_cost (#1 encode hotspot): per-coefficient
    context-indexed cost-table loop. `perf annotate` confirms scalar
    ldr/cmp/csel/csinc/madd — data-dependent table indexing that is not
    vectorizable. Already remapped/padded/direct-indexed to the branchless
    ceiling (csel/csinc on ARM = the cmov path on x86).
  - encode record_coeff: serial token recording; documented stack-buffer attempt
    was net-negative (memset overhead exceeded savings).

There is no un-vectorized hot kernel falling to scalar where a NEON path should
exist, and no scalar fallback firing where a NEON path already exists. Speculative
micro-tuning of an already-NEON kernel with no measured deficiency would risk the
ZERO-TOLERANCE pixel-correctness gate for unmeasured gain. Per the
"measured-win-only" discipline, NO source perf change is shipped for zenwebp.

CORRECTNESS GATE
----------------
- `cargo test --release --lib` on the ARM box (base 59568e89): pass (see commit log).
- No codec source changed, so encode/decode output is byte-identical to base by
  construction; the only code added is bench plumbing (corpus fallback) + a
  profiling-only example gated behind the `_profiling` feature.

